":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Bit Manipulation","Brainteaser","Array","Math","Dynamic Programming","Game Theory"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Alice and Bob take turns playing a game with **Alice starting first**.\n\nIn this game, there are `n` piles of stones. On each player's turn, the player should remove any **positive** number of stones from a non-empty pile **of his or her choice**. The first player who cannot make a move loses, and the other player wins.\n\nGiven an integer array `piles`, where `piles[i]` is the number of stones in the `i^(th)` pile, return `true`* if Alice wins, or *`false`* if Bob wins*.\n\nBoth Alice and Bob play **optimally**.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: piles = [1]\nOutput: true\nExplanation: There is only one possible scenario:\n- On the first turn, Alice removes one stone from the first pile. piles = [0].\n- On the second turn, there are no stones left for Bob to remove. Alice wins.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: piles = [1,1]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: It can be proven that Bob will always win. One possible scenario is:\n- On the first turn, Alice removes one stone from the first pile. piles = [0,1].\n- On the second turn, Bob removes one stone from the second pile. piles = [0,0].\n- On the third turn, there are no stones left for Alice to remove. Bob wins.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: piles = [1,2,3]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: It can be proven that Bob will always win. One possible scenario is:\n- On the first turn, Alice removes three stones from the third pile. piles = [1,2,0].\n- On the second turn, Bob removes one stone from the second pile. piles = [1,1,0].\n- On the third turn, Alice removes one stone from the first pile. piles = [0,1,0].\n- On the fourth turn, Bob removes one stone from the second pile. piles = [0,0,0].